1105
01:01:03,727 --> 01:01:06,162
<i>"It's time to get back to
work. Let's do our thing."</i>

1106
01:01:06,263 --> 01:01:09,107
<i>And after the movie was done,
he didn't do any more acting.</i>

1107
01:01:09,216 --> 01:01:10,843
<i>He went on to work
for the Steamship Authority</i>

1108
01:01:10,934 --> 01:01:12,459
<i>with my brother, Tommy.</i>

1109
01:01:12,569 --> 01:01:15,311
And that's where he worked
until his passing.

1110
01:01:17,841 --> 01:01:21,209
<i>We really miss him.
We really miss him.</i>

1111
01:01:24,848 --> 01:01:29,058
<i>Perhaps no islander gained
more notoriety for his involvement in Jaws</i>

1112
01:01:29,135 --> 01:01:31,035
<i>than the late Craig Kings bury.</i>

1113
01:01:31,872 --> 01:01:33,601
<i>Craig's gruff and blustery demeanor</i>

1114
01:01:33,673 --> 01:01:36,392
<i>had made him a local legend
in his own right.</i>

1115
01:01:36,493 --> 01:01:41,192
<i>And his portrayal of fisherman Ben
Gardner, a favorite among Jaws fans.</i>

1116
01:01:41,298 --> 01:01:46,759
<i>They advertised for
some person who was a fisherman, a local,</i>

1117
01:01:47,087 --> 01:01:49,715
<i>who could help Robert Shaw
with his accent.</i>

1118
01:01:49,789 --> 01:01:53,771
<i>Robert was a refined British
actor until he met my father,</i>

1119
01:01:53,877 --> 01:01:56,471
<i>and then my father told him stories about</i>

1120
01:01:56,580 --> 01:01:59,140
<i>this island and the people that live here,</i>

1121
01:01:59,432 --> 01:02:03,300
and, unfortunately, I think
Robert Shaw believed them.

1122
01:02:03,370 --> 01:02:06,271
He fell hook, line and sinker,
and he began to repeat them.

1123
01:02:06,356 --> 01:02:08,267
<i>He was interviewed on the air,</i>

1124
01:02:08,358 --> 01:02:10,383
<i>telling these totally outrageous stories</i>

1125
01:02:10,477 --> 01:02:11,854
<i>about the local community.</i>

1126
01:02:11,962 --> 01:02:13,043
…the rich people here.

1127
01:02:13,113 --> 01:02:15,389
There's a lot of skeletons in
the cupboard here, you know.

1128
01:02:15,482 --> 01:02:17,530
There's more incest going on
in Martha's Vineyard

1129
01:02:17,634 --> 01:02:21,286
than probably any state
in the United States.

1130
01:02:21,371 --> 01:02:24,898
They were mostly lies, which
is what my father was best at.

1131
01:02:25,175 --> 01:02:27,758
They'll wish their fathers
hadn't met their mothers…

1132
01:02:29,346 --> 01:02:32,407
My mother, when I took her
to see the movie in Boston,

1133
01:02:32,499 --> 01:02:34,547
we came out of the theater and she said,

1134
01:02:34,651 --> 01:02:36,665
<i>"That Spielberg, he's a genius.</i>

1135
01:02:36,736 --> 01:02:40,548
<i>"Finally, somebody has found a
use for your father's empty head."</i>

1136
01:02:41,408 --> 01:02:45,026
<i>Of course, Craig's most
memorable scene did involve his head,</i>

1137
01:02:45,262 --> 01:02:46,627
<i>but not the rest of him.</i>

1138
01:02:46,730 --> 01:02:49,028
<i>In fact, it didn't even
take place at the Vineyard.</i>

1139
01:02:49,215 --> 01:02:52,560
<i>Three thousand miles away
in Van Nuys, California,</i>

1140
01:02:52,669 --> 01:02:55,195
<i>Spielberg resourcefully created that</i>

1141
01:02:55,305 --> 01:02:57,831
<i>most shocking moment as an insert shot,</i>

1142
01:02:58,041 --> 01:03:01,204
<i>and he used little more than
a foam life-cast of Kings bury</i>

1143
01:03:01,311 --> 01:03:02,642
<i>and a swimming pool.</i>

1144
01:03:02,946 --> 01:03:05,643
<i>Steven had just
come from the answer print with Verna</i>

1145
01:03:05,749 --> 01:03:07,899
at Universal and had signed off on it,

1146
01:03:07,968 --> 01:03:10,551
and here we were on that very eve,

1147
01:03:10,654 --> 01:03:14,454
doing an extra shot that we were
gonna try to get in the next day.

1148
01:03:14,541 --> 01:03:16,316
That scene had already been shot.

1149
01:03:16,493 --> 01:03:18,655
<i>But it wasn't done to shock the audience,</i>

1150
01:03:18,762 --> 01:03:20,105
<i>and so I went to Verna Fields',</i>

1151
01:03:20,180 --> 01:03:21,454
<i>my film editor's swimming pool,</i>

1152
01:03:21,548 --> 01:03:23,448
borrowed her pool,
'cause I didn't have one,

1153
01:03:23,516 --> 01:03:25,541
I didn't have enough money to
have a swimming pool in those days,

1154
01:03:25,618 --> 01:03:27,029
because <i>Jaws</i> hadn't come out yet,

1155
01:03:27,137 --> 01:03:28,514
and I was a poor director then.

1156
01:03:28,672 --> 01:03:31,403
We had a small replica of a hull

1157
01:03:31,508 --> 01:03:33,840
that I put together
in Joe Alves' driveway.

1158
01:03:33,927 --> 01:03:36,305
<i>And I basically held my breath underwater</i>

1159
01:03:36,413 --> 01:03:39,474
and put the head of Ben
Gardner through that hull

1160
01:03:39,566 --> 01:03:41,978
when Frankie Sparks came up
with the flashlight.

1161
01:03:46,456 --> 01:03:50,199
<i>I remember, I timed it
to get maximum shock effect.</i>

1162
01:03:55,098 --> 01:03:57,157
<i>This is the pool where Steven Spielberg</i>

1163
01:03:57,267 --> 01:03:59,326
<i>filmed the Ben Gardner sequence.</i>

1164
01:03:59,436 --> 01:04:01,154
And that was done right here.
Very famous.

1165
01:04:01,221 --> 01:04:04,236
Scary. Scary moment.

1166
01:04:04,341 --> 01:04:06,867
<i>What was the most
satisfying edit you did in</i> Jaws?

1167
01:04:06,960 --> 01:04:09,440
The most satisfying edit, I have to say,

1168
01:04:09,546 --> 01:04:11,594
was the face coming out of the boat.

1169
01:04:11,664 --> 01:04:13,154
Because when I went to that preview,

1170
01:04:13,233 --> 01:04:15,884
and that audience just
went six feet off their seats

1171
01:04:15,969 --> 01:04:20,623
and let out this incredible
scream, that was really satisfying.

1172
01:04:20,724 --> 01:04:24,433
When we found this place, it was
still full of her reels just sitting there,

1173
01:04:24,511 --> 01:04:27,412
<i>but it was amazing treasure to find.</i>

1174
01:04:28,932 --> 01:04:31,663
These are some footlockers
that we found at the house.

1175
01:04:31,768 --> 01:04:35,204
These came back from Martha's
Vineyard, from the shoot there,

1176
01:04:35,305 --> 01:04:39,105
and as you can see, "Verna
Fields, editorial <i>Jaws, "</i>

1177
01:04:39,209 --> 01:04:41,007
on the cover of this one.

1178
01:04:41,111 --> 01:04:43,637
And inside, there are several film reels

1179
01:04:43,747 --> 01:04:47,308
of Verna's work still
kept in these boxes here.

1180
01:04:47,417 --> 01:04:50,682
This is full of different
films that she made.

1181
01:04:51,871 --> 01:04:53,999
Yeah, she had set up
her editing facility here

1182
01:04:54,074 --> 01:04:57,806
<i>and edited all of her films
in this building right here.</i>

1183
01:04:57,911 --> 01:05:00,380
<i>It's kind of cool
that this humble, simple room</i>

1184
01:05:00,447 --> 01:05:03,974
<i>is where one of the greatest
movies ever was put together.</i>

1185
01:05:04,968 --> 01:05:05,968
What are we looking for?

1186
01:05:06,069 --> 01:05:07,764
We're looking for a nice place to show

1187
01:05:07,871 --> 01:05:10,533
that Quint refuses to slow down the boat.

1188
01:05:12,025 --> 01:05:17,680
And here we have the Moviola
that Verna Fields used to edit Jaws.

1189
01:05:17,781 --> 01:05:21,558
Every second of the Jaws film
passed through this machine

1190
01:05:21,634 --> 01:05:24,353
by the hands of Verna Fields.
That's special.

1191
01:05:24,454 --> 01:05:28,413
Doesn't look very pretty now,
but maybe someday, it will again.

1192
01:05:29,793 --> 01:05:31,511
<i>Verna and I worked in her pool house</i>

1193
01:05:31,578 --> 01:05:34,354
<i>shoulder to shoulder for a
long time on that Moviola.</i>

1194
01:05:34,481 --> 01:05:37,940
And Verna did a great job
with her biorhythms.

1195
01:05:38,017 --> 01:05:42,796
Creating a biorhythm for Jaws that
was just the right kind of tautness,

1196
01:05:42,906 --> 01:05:45,750
like a violin string to play
a very, very high note.

1197
01:05:48,645 --> 01:05:50,443
It can't take that much pressure.

1198
01:05:53,183 --> 01:05:54,491
That's the spot, Steve.

1199
01:05:59,088 --> 01:06:01,534
<i>My husband tells me you're in sharks.</i>

1200
01:06:04,344 --> 01:06:07,655
Excuse me. Yes. I've never
heard it quite put that way.

1201
01:06:07,730 --> 01:06:09,141
But yes, I am.

1202
01:06:09,549 --> 01:06:10,710
I love sharks.

1203
01:06:11,151 --> 01:06:12,459
<i>Yeah, I love them.</i>

1204
01:06:14,003 --> 01:06:17,769
<i>I think the fascination
with sharks comes from many things.</i>

1205
01:06:17,841 --> 01:06:21,402
<i>One, they are the last surviving predator</i>

1206
01:06:21,478 --> 01:06:23,503
<i>that poses a genuine threat to man</i>

1207
01:06:23,580 --> 01:06:26,561
<i>in an environment
in which he chooses to go.</i>

1208
01:06:28,635 --> 01:06:32,219
E. O. Wilson said, "We
don't just fear our predators,

1209
01:06:32,305 --> 01:06:34,023
"we are transfixed by them."

1210
01:06:34,574 --> 01:06:36,838
<i>Prone to weave stories and fables</i>

1211
01:06:36,943 --> 01:06:42,109
<i>because fascination breeds
preparedness, and preparedness, survival.</i>

1212
01:06:42,215 --> 01:06:46,402
<i>In a deeply tribal sense, he
said, "We love our monsters."</i>

1213
01:06:48,488 --> 01:06:53,221
<i>I believe that worldwide, young
children, all male children at least,</i>

1214
01:06:53,326 --> 01:06:56,193
<i>have a fascination with
either sharks or dinosaurs.</i>

1215
01:06:56,296 --> 01:06:57,878
Very big shark.

1216
01:06:58,047 --> 01:07:00,823
<i>And in my case, I was
able to grow up around here</i>

1217
01:07:00,934 --> 01:07:03,960
<i>in Nantucket where
sharks were in proliferation.</i>

1218
01:07:04,053 --> 01:07:07,421
<i>So I was able to fix my
fascination on sharks.</i>

1219
01:07:10,777 --> 01:07:13,462
<i>One couple whose fixed fascination</i>

1220
01:07:13,530 --> 01:07:17,194
<i>led to their preeminence in the
field of great white shark research</i>

1221
01:07:17,267 --> 01:07:21,534
<i>was husband and wife team
Ron and Valerie Taylor of Australia.</i>

1222
01:07:21,704 --> 01:07:25,106
<i>Their combined experience
throughout the '60s and '70s</i>

1223
01:07:25,174 --> 01:07:27,688
<i>documenting these elusive animals</i>

1224
01:07:27,794 --> 01:07:31,128
<i>made them the perfect fit
for the Jaws creative team.</i>

1225
01:07:31,231 --> 01:07:34,007
<i>They were commissioned
to shoot live shark footage</i>

1226
01:07:34,083 --> 01:07:37,428
<i>for the picture's climactic cage sequence.</i>

1227
01:07:37,537 --> 01:07:40,063
<i>The assignment would prove
to be almost as harrowing</i>

1228
01:07:40,173 --> 01:07:41,720
<i>as anything in the film itself.</i>

1229
01:07:42,909 --> 01:07:44,399
<i>I told them that there's a problem,</i>

1230
01:07:44,494 --> 01:07:48,806
because our sharks on average
are only about 13 feet in length,

1231
01:07:48,915 --> 01:07:52,328
and yet your mechanical shark
is 26 feet in length.

1232
01:07:52,402 --> 01:07:54,018
And they said, "Well, there's no problem.

1233
01:07:54,103 --> 01:07:57,915
"We'll send you a small man
and small cages."

1234
01:07:58,107 --> 01:08:03,625
We built a scaled down cage, and
we tried a dummy and that didn't work,

1235
01:08:03,730 --> 01:08:08,725
so we found a small person that
said that they could scuba dive.

1236
01:08:08,835 --> 01:08:11,395
<i>Carl wasn't an experienced diver.</i>

1237
01:08:11,571 --> 01:08:15,633
<i>So we gave him an introduction to
diving just down on the waterfront</i>

1238
01:08:15,742 --> 01:08:18,427
<i>and took him out to Dangerous Reef.</i>

1239
01:08:18,678 --> 01:08:23,332
<i>And when he saw his first great
white shark, he was terrified.</i>

1240
01:08:23,416 --> 01:08:27,478
But to give him his credit, Carl
actually did get into the cage

1241
01:08:27,587 --> 01:08:30,534
with these great, big, dangerous looking

1242
01:08:30,607 --> 01:08:31,950
<i>great white sharks swimming around.</i>

1243
01:08:32,058 --> 01:08:35,005
<i>Dangerous looking because we
had put a lot of bait in the water</i>

1244
01:08:35,078 --> 01:08:37,024
<i>to attract them to our cages.</i>

1245
01:08:38,498 --> 01:08:41,183
Joe Alves came into my office one day

1246
01:08:41,250 --> 01:08:44,811
with his hand behind his back and
he said, "Bill, we've screwed up."

1247
01:08:44,887 --> 01:08:48,869
And he held up the tanks
that had been miniaturized.

1248
01:08:48,975 --> 01:08:52,878
He said, "That little guy
only has eight minutes of air."

1249
01:08:53,146 --> 01:08:54,557
What we were not thinking

1250
01:08:54,631 --> 01:08:59,296
is that a small person still sucks
up as much air as a large person,

1251
01:08:59,369 --> 01:09:01,417
and the tanks were very small.

1252
01:09:01,521 --> 01:09:03,740
So, immediately, when he sort of panicked,

1253
01:09:03,806 --> 01:09:06,685
<i>he sucked up all the air out of the tank.</i>

1254
01:09:06,793 --> 01:09:10,252
<i>Carl was very
reluctant. He was afraid. Very afraid.</i>

1255
01:09:10,363 --> 01:09:14,573
The production manager was
calling out to him to get in the cage,

1256
01:09:14,651 --> 01:09:18,804
and he was very slow about it,
and just as he was about to climb in,

1257
01:09:18,905 --> 01:09:21,647
a <i>large shark tried to swim over it</i>

1258
01:09:21,741 --> 01:09:24,438
<i>and got its head stuck in the bridle,</i>

1259
01:09:24,544 --> 01:09:28,128
<i>and of course, it was
trapped and it went crazy.</i>

1260
01:09:28,197 --> 01:09:31,599
<i>And the tail went into the
back part of the little boat</i>

1261
01:09:31,668 --> 01:09:34,399
<i>and tore out all the hydraulic cables</i>

1262
01:09:34,487 --> 01:09:37,184
that took fuel and fluid to the motors.

1263
01:09:37,290 --> 01:09:40,191
And it started to run across
the deck, and as it did that,

1264
01:09:40,293 --> 01:09:43,627
<i>the tail flicked Carl's</i> face.

1265
01:09:43,730 --> 01:09:46,461
<i>And Carl just stood there,
and he looked up and he said,</i>

1266
01:09:46,566 --> 01:09:51,367
"Is that my blood?" And it
was actually the hydraulic fluid.

1267
01:09:51,471 --> 01:09:53,667
And we never got him in the water again.

1268
01:09:54,774 --> 01:09:58,938
<i>If Carl had been in that
cage, he would have lost his life.</i>

1269
01:09:59,045 --> 01:10:02,629
There wasn't much I
could've done to get over there.

1270
01:10:02,699 --> 01:10:04,997
The shark was still tangled,
and thrashing around

1271
01:10:05,068 --> 01:10:07,912
<i>and tangled in the cage on the bottom.</i>

1272
01:10:08,004 --> 01:10:10,314
<i>Carl would have been in there and drowned.</i>

1273
01:10:10,423 --> 01:10:12,790
<i>So his reluctance saved his life.</i>

1274
01:10:19,499 --> 01:10:22,127
1,100 men went into the water.

1275
01:10:22,235 --> 01:10:24,397
Vessel went down in 12 minutes.

1276
01:10:26,606 --> 01:10:30,292
Didn't see the first shark
for about half an hour. Tiger…

1277
01:10:30,359 --> 01:10:32,600
<i>A very little credited writer who made</i>

1278
01:10:32,712 --> 01:10:34,191
<i>the biggest breakthrough on</i> Jaws,

1279
01:10:34,263 --> 01:10:36,777
<i>which was a writer named Howard Sackler,</i>

1280
01:10:36,883 --> 01:10:39,978
<i>whose idea it was to give
Quint the Indianapolis speech,</i>

1281
01:10:40,086 --> 01:10:42,828
even though it was John
Milius who wrote the speech,

1282
01:10:42,905 --> 01:10:45,624
I mean, Howard Sackler wrote
like two paragraphs this big,

1283
01:10:45,725 --> 01:10:50,470
<i>John Milius wrote a nine page
monologue for Quint to say.</i>

1284
01:10:50,563 --> 01:10:53,112
<i>And then when Robert Shaw,
who himself was a writer,</i>

1285
01:10:53,199 --> 01:10:57,067
<i>of The Man in the</i> Glass <i>Booth
read Milius' 10 pages,</i>

1286
01:10:57,170 --> 01:10:59,901
he says, "I can't go on for 10, 15 minutes

1287
01:11:00,006 --> 01:11:02,748
"just talking.
Let me have a crack at it."

1288
01:11:02,842 --> 01:11:07,757
Shaw took the speech and
himself edited it down to five pages.

1289
01:11:07,847 --> 01:11:10,646
And that was the whole evolution
of how that speech was told,

1290
01:11:10,750 --> 01:11:13,549
but it did come from the mind
of Howard Sackler,

1291
01:11:13,653 --> 01:11:15,917
who remembered the actual
Indianapolis incident

1292
01:11:16,022 --> 01:11:17,535
and suggested that Quint…

1293
01:11:17,607 --> 01:11:20,292
That that become a Rosetta
stone for Quint's entire character.

1294
01:11:20,393 --> 01:11:22,612
Steven said, "Oh, my God."

1295
01:11:22,678 --> 01:11:27,366
That's the whole impetus,
that's the whole spine of Quint.

1296
01:11:27,467 --> 01:11:33,918
He's not really just crazy, but he
has a case out for these sharks.

1297
01:11:33,990 --> 01:11:36,038
You know, by the end of that first dawn…

1298
01:11:38,211 --> 01:11:39,519
we lost 100 men.

1299
01:11:41,364 --> 01:11:43,640
I don't know how many
sharks. Maybe 1,000.

1300
01:11:43,733 --> 01:11:46,384
I don't know how many men,
they averaged six an hour.

1301
01:11:46,486 --> 01:11:51,390
<i>The USS Indianapolis was top
secret when Peter wrote the book.</i>

1302
01:11:51,491 --> 01:11:55,906
So it wasn't in it. He
would've used it, I think.

1303
01:11:55,978 --> 01:11:58,288
And then, before the making of the film,

1304
01:11:58,381 --> 01:12:00,657
it had been unclassified
and Steven used it.

1305
01:12:00,750 --> 01:12:04,232
<i>The world learned of the
USS Indianapolis through Jaws</i>

1306
01:12:04,337 --> 01:12:09,025
<i>and it was a perfectly accurate
depiction insofar as I know.</i>

1307
01:12:09,091 --> 01:12:12,607
<i>Peter's domestic housekeeper
called in the day after the movie opened</i>

1308
01:12:12,712 --> 01:12:16,444
and she said that she wasn't
coming in to work the next day.

1309
01:12:16,549 --> 01:12:17,983
And when he said, "Why," she said,

1310
01:12:18,084 --> 01:12:20,246
<i>"My son was on the USS Indianapolis,</i>

1311
01:12:20,353 --> 01:12:22,447
"and I never knew how he died until now."

1312
01:12:25,558 --> 01:12:28,209
He'd been bitten in half, below the waist.

1313
01:12:31,013 --> 01:12:33,141
<i>The U. S.
naval cruiser which delivered</i>

1314
01:12:33,216 --> 01:12:35,264
<i>the atomic bomb used on Hiroshima</i>

1315
01:12:35,368 --> 01:12:36,802
<i>completed her mission,</i>

1316
01:12:36,903 --> 01:12:39,736
<i>but was then sunk by a Japanese submarine.</i>

1317
01:12:41,307 --> 01:12:45,687
<i>Out of her complement
of 1,196 sailors and Marines,</i>

1318
01:12:45,761 --> 01:12:48,742
